3a) Write a HTML program, that makes use of <article>, <aside>, <figure>, <figcaption>, <footer>, 

<header>, <main>, <nav>, <section>, <div>, <span> tags.

Aim: Write a HTML program, that makes use of <article>, <aside>, <figure>, <figcaption>, <footer>, 

<header>, <main>, <nav>, <section>, <div>, <span> tags.

Description:

• <header> contains the website title and navigation links using <nav>.

• <main> holds the main content, divided into <section>s.

• Each <section> includes an <article> representing an individual post or item.

• <figure> and <figcaption> are used to add images with captions.

• <aside> provides related or side content (like tips or ads).

• <footer> shows the closing content such as copyright.

• <div> is used for general layout grouping, and <span> for inline styling or highlighting text.

Program:

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html lang="en">

<head>

 <meta charset="UTF-8" />

 <title>Semantic HTML Example</title>

</head>

<body>

 <header>

 <h1>My Blog</h1>

 <nav>

 <a href="#home">Home</a> |

 <a href="#posts">Posts</a> |

 <a href="#about">About</a>

 </nav>

 </header>

 <main>

 <section id="posts">

 <article>

 <header><h2>First Post</h2></header>

 <figure>

 <img src="https://via.placeholder.com/150" alt="Placeholder" />

 <figcaption>Sample Image</figcaption>

 </figure>

 <p>This is an example <span>article</span> demonstrating semantic tags.</p>

 <footer>Posted on Oct 7, 2025</footer>

 </article>

 <aside>

 <p>Related info or ads go here.</p>

 </aside>

 </section>

 <div>

 <p>A generic container using &lt;div&gt; for layout.</p>

 </div>

 </main>

 <footer>

 <p>© 2025 My Blog</p>

 </footer>

</body>

</html>
3 b) Write a HTML program, to embed audio and video into HTML web page

Aim: Write a HTML program, to embed audio and video into HTML web page

Description:

• The <audio> tag is used to embed sound files like music or voice in a web page.

• The <video> tag allows embedding video clips directly into the page.

• Both tags support formats like MP3 (audio) and MP4 (video).

• The controls attribute adds play, pause, and volume options.

• Optional attributes include autoplay, loop, muted, and poster (for video).

• You can use multiple <source> tags to support different file types for compatibility.

Program:

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html>

<head>

<title>Embedding Audio and Video</title>

</head>

<body>

<h2>HTML5 Audio and Video Embedding</h2>

<!-- Embed Audio -->

<section>

<h3>Audio Example:</h3>

<audio controls>

<source src="https://www.soundhelix.com/examples/mp3/SoundHelix-Song-1.mp3" 

type="audio/mpeg"> Your browser does not support the audio element.

</audio>

</section>

<br>

<!-- Embed Video -->

<section>

<h3>Video Example:</h3>

<video width="600" height="340" controls>

<source src="https://www.w3schools.com/html/mov_bbb.mp4" type="video/mp4">

Your browser does not support the video tag.

</video>

</section>

</body>

</html>

Output:



3 c) Write a program to apply different types (or levels of styles or style specification formats) -

inline, internal, external styles to HTML elements. (identify selector, property and value).

Aim: Write a program to apply different types (or levels of styles or style specification formats) -inline, 

internal, external styles to HTML elements. (identify selector, property and value).

Description:

CSS Style Specification Formats:

1. Inline CSS – inside the HTML tag using style attribute

2. Internal CSS – inside a <style> block in the <head>

3. External CSS – in a separate .css file and linked using <link> (simulated here)

Each CSS rule has:

• Selector – the HTML element(s) to style

• Property – the style attribute to change

• Value – the setting for that property

Syntax:

selector {

property: value;

}

Example 1 (from inline CSS):

<h1 style="color: blue;">Hello</h1>

• Selector: h1 (implied, though it's inline)

• Property: color

• Value: blue

Example 2 (from internal CSS):

h2 {

 color: darkgreen;

 font-family: Georgia, serif;

}

Selector: h2

• First:

o Property: color

o Value: darkgreen

• Second:

o Property: font-family

o Value: Georgia, serif

Example 3 (from external CSS):

.external-paragraph {

 font-size: 18px;

 color: darkred;

}

Selector: .external-paragraph (a class selector)

• First:

o Property: font-size

o Value: 18px

• Second:

o Property: color

o Value: darkred

Program:

index.html:

<!DOCTYPE html>

<html lang="en">

<head>

 <meta charset="UTF-8">

 <title>CSS Styles Demo</title>
<!-- Internal CSS -->

 <style>

 h2 {

 color: darkgreen;

 font-family: Georgia, serif;

 }

 .internal-box {

 background-color: lightyellow;

 border: 2px solid orange;

 padding: 10px;

 }

 </style>

 <!-- External CSS -->

 <link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="styles.css">

</head>

<body>

 <h1 style="color: blue; font-size: 28px;">Inline Styled Heading (h1)</h1>

 <h2>Internal Styled Heading (h2)</h2>

 <div class="internal-box">

 This box uses <strong>internal CSS</strong> for styling.

 </div>

 <br>

 <p class="external-paragraph">

 This paragraph is styled using <strong>external CSS</strong>.

 </p>

</body>

</html>

styles.css:

/* External CSS styles */

.external-paragraph {

 font-size: 18px;

 color: darkred;

 background-color: #f0f0f0;

 padding: 12px;

 border-left: 4px solid red;

}

Output


